  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3112913272" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3112913272" />
    <a title="Regina Andreassen" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6417302-regina-andreassen"><img alt="Regina Andreassen" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1613438964p2/6417302.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3112913272?book_show_action=true">Nov 30, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Regina Andreassen" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Regina Andreassen" href="/user/show/6417302-regina-andreassen">Regina Andreassen</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780552776387" href="/book/show/12600284-the-moral-landscape">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3112913272" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6695618560330217592">2.25 stars. What a disappointment! This is such a juvenile work! There is no much science here and there is no much philosophy either! If you want to gain a further understanding of science and its connection to morality/ethics, then please subscribe to relevant academic journals or buy some books written but prominent researchers in the field of study (some of these scholars are briefly referenced by Harris in this book). There are also excellent philosophical treatises written by acclaimed sch</span>
  <span id="freeText6695618560330217592" style="display:none">2.25 stars. What a disappointment! This is such a juvenile work! There is no much science here and there is no much philosophy either! If you want to gain a further understanding of science and its connection to morality/ethics, then please subscribe to relevant academic journals or buy some books written but prominent researchers in the field of study (some of these scholars are briefly referenced by Harris in this book). There are also excellent philosophical treatises written by acclaimed scholars, scholars who Sam Harris may try to emulate but could never equal. In The Moral Landscape, Sam Harris is not suggesting anything original and he is not really developing a cohesive argument either. Admittedly, Sam Harris has good intentions, however, he is a mediocre and unconvincing writer.<br /><br />Sam Harris starts his argument well, he can be rather engaging, yet somehow, after one chapter he loses his momentum. In this book, Harris seems unable to develop his ideas coherently as he constantly deviates from the main subject of the book. Although I am an agnostic, I am bored of reading Sam Harris's exceedingly biased critique of religion, especially when religion is not the main object of discussion. I did not buy this book to continue reading Harris's antitheist verbiage; I bought The Moral Landscape because I wanted to ascertain the foundations and validity of Harris's scientific position regarding morality. As I already noted, Harris starts his argument well alas, he just cannot help himself, as soon as religion enters his mind that is all he can think about it! As a result, he ends up developing a disorganised, unoriginal, superficial, and epistemologically feeble argument. In The Moral Landscape, Harris also references some of the ideas he espouses in Free Will; whilst I agree with some of those ideas, in The Moral Landscape he does not explore those notions effectively, thus, he fails to present a congruent and cohesive argument. The 'free will' section of The Moral Landscape felt like a first draft, not like a final copy, ready to be published. <br /><br /> Furthermore, I was disappointed by the outdated/inaccurate information provided in this book. Let me provide some examples, even if they come across as pedantic. Harris is still employing these two words: psychopathy and sociopathy, words which psychiatrists, psychologists, neuropsychologists, and neuroscientists do not tend to utilise anymore for those terms do not refer to any official diagnosis; the modern classification as recognised in the Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders(DSM-5 manual) is Antisocial Personality Disorders (ASPD). Sam Harris also equates psychopathy and sociopathy to narcissism and grandiosity, but these are different personality disorders. Has Sam Harris heard of the term comorbidity? I am rolling my eyes! Okay, I am probably acting like a judgemental snob- and I am probably one! I understand that Sam Harris is writing for a general audience, for people who understand the implications of psycopathy and sociopathy as portrayed in popular culture, hence, I understand that he is trying to connect with that audience by using terms that are employed colloquially, but the fact is that Sam Harris is writing a book about science, ergo, he should be educating his audience rather than perpetuating misinformation or misusing terms - especially nowadays when certain terms are used rather loosely by people who do not work in the field of sciences and who do not seem to know the difference among various terms. <br /><br /> I was also shocked by Harris's completely dismissal of the work of other outstanding scientists who in spite of their theist or religious views have achieved far more recognition in the world of sciences than Harris has achieved; these are scholars whose contribution to the scientific world is far more valuable than Harris's. For example, in his chapter Religion, Harris dedicates a few pages to pummel a very respected researcher: Francis Collins, the head of the Human Genome Project, merely because he is a Christian (he was raised Episcopalian). Yes, Collins is religious, however, Collins does not contest irrefutable scientific facts, au contraire, his scientific position is respectable, and he has received quite a few accolades. This validates my criticism: if we consider the subject that the Moral Landscape attempted to discuss, dedicating pages of the book to relentlessly attack Francis Collins makes no sense whatsoever; it is incredibly infantile and vicious; is Harris envious of Collins's success? or does Harris perhaps feel that Colling is undeserving of the praise because he is a Christian? Does Harris not know that holding a theist or religious position does not necessarily mean that that person is 'hard-core religious', a evolution-denialist or a cruel uneducated bigot? One thing is certain: after all those years spent by Harris studying at UCLA and Stanford, years in which he was surrounded by other members of the academia, Harris still has not learn. He still seem unable to apprehend the basic tenets of science. The validity of a person's work or academic credentials cannot be disputed solely based on an individual's personal religious beliefs, cultural attitudes, politics, age, personality, etc. Do I sound too critical of Harris? Surely not as critical as he is of almost every other scholar/individual who dares to object his views! My criticism of Harris's approach to religion is echoed by most respected agnostics, atheists, as well as theist scientists for they have also identified Sam Harris's inability to adopt a reflexive, balanced, and equanimous position whenever religion enters the discussion -and even if religion is not in the discussion you can trust Harris to bring religion to the forefront of the discussion! <br /><br />Frankly, after reading his chapter on religion, I have reached the conclusion that Sam Harris does not understand the difference between being an active member of a religion and simply believing in a god or having some sort of spirituality. He is predominantly speaking to a US audience and attacking Fundamentalists, but he is also misinforming the general non-theist audience about what happens across the developed World. For instance, he makes some inaccurate generalisations about religion in the Netherlands and all Scandinavian countries, because he equates religion with extremism; he ignores the existence of basic theism/spirituality that is not overtly expressed. Harris also makes some spurious claims about Scandinavian countries and what he insinuates is their almost absence of religion or theist views and its connection to their lifestyles. How is he selecting his sources? Moreover, Sam Harris has conveniently excluded Australia from his list of the countries which have the best quality of life in the World. I suspect that Harries has ignored Australia deliberately because Australia's case shows the weaknesses of his claims: most people here in Australia are not atheists nor are most Australians anti-theists, and inasmuch as most Australians are not actively practicing a particular religion and Australia is widely a secular society the census reveals that most people residing in Australia still hold some theistic or spiritual views and culturally Australian values are still predominantly influenced by Christianity, with Catholicism being the most common religion in the country. This, I conjecture is something that Harris preferred not to disclose, it is either that or he is ill-informed, which speaks poorly of him as an author, since this information is readily available. Unfortunately, Harris does not acknowledge that for several years Australia has been doing better than Denmark, Sweden, and The Netherlands, ; this is established in the Human Development Index ranking, so I reiterate: I am suspicious of this exclusion. Why are you cherry picking your information, Sam? Or are you just parroting others because you are too lazy to double check your data? <br /><br />I must point out some massive errors that in my opinion suggest that Sam Harris did not undertake meticulous research before publishing this book. This is one of them: by the time Harris published The Moral Landscape, Clifford Geertz was already dead, accordingly, I have no idea why Harris referred to Clifford Geertz as if he were still alive. It is also evident that Harris does not really understand Clifford Geertz's position on morality, hence, I speculate that Harris has probably read a couple of chapters of Geertz's famous Interpretation of Cultures, and based on that Harris has wrongly inferred that he knows where exactly Geertz stood in the moral debate. Clearly, Harris does not know the magnitude of Clifford Geertz's contribution to the field of anthropology, the development of ethnography, and his legacy to the social sciences in general. <br /><br />Will Sam Harris ever learn? I doubt it, because he is rather conceited and, since he has built a following, he will always sell books. We must keep in mind that many of his fans are people who do not have unlimited or free access to peer-reviewed articles, most of his radical followers are not part of the academic world, and therefore, only understand sciences superficially, ergo, they are usually unaware of all the controversy that surrounds Sam Harris and all the criticism he has received from other academics. Ironically, I too will probably continue buying Harris's future books, just out of curiosity and because I feel like giving him another chance! I want to believe that he will learn as he grows older! There is some potential there, Sam, dear!<br /><br />I have probably forgotten a few things I wanted to say, and I have no doubts that my review is filled with typographical errors and I should probably double check the syntax, but I won't because if I go back to read my review I will stay here for at least another couple of hours, editing, rewriting, adding sentences, and well, stressing out! I have already left some comments below other people’s reviews. It would not surprise me to see some of Harris's followers coming here and attacking me...to them I can only say this: I am an agnostic, I do not hate Sam Harris, but I detest seeing authors uttering mediocre arguments but presented as 'ground-breaking ideas', just to sell a book. Do you want to read real science and arguments about morality backed up by science? Spend your money wisely, subscribe to relevant journals, listen to what respected scientists think of Harris's work! Do not blindly follow him. This is the thing: Just as Dan Brown is not a reliable historian, because his knowledge of history is shallow, the same can be said about Sam Harris and science! Harris's understanding of sciences is above the average but it is still not good enough for a scientist. The same applies to his knowledge of philosophy and anthropology. It is really that simple.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6695618560330217592" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


