    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_760072774" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/760072774" />
    <a title="Jeremy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5920051-jeremy"><img alt="Jeremy" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1433655412p2/5920051.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/760072774?book_show_action=true">Nov 08, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jeremy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jeremy" href="/user/show/5920051-jeremy">Jeremy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer760072774" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4087308366382797533">The book is essentially a combination of soft targets and old news. The Taliban aren&apos;t an ideal moral society! Who knew? Fulfillment is to be preferred to abject misery? What revolutionary advice! Refuting religious fundamentalism and some extreme-left versions of prescriptive cultural relativism, while valid enough, is also vapid and easy work, beyond the fact that it&apos;s merely rehashing work that Harris has done better elsewhere. What is genuinely worse, however, is that Harris seems to think t</span>
  <span id="freeText4087308366382797533" style="display:none">The book is essentially a combination of soft targets and old news. The Taliban aren't an ideal moral society! Who knew? Fulfillment is to be preferred to abject misery? What revolutionary advice! Refuting religious fundamentalism and some extreme-left versions of prescriptive cultural relativism, while valid enough, is also vapid and easy work, beyond the fact that it's merely rehashing work that Harris has done better elsewhere. What is genuinely worse, however, is that Harris seems to think that religious fundamentalism and prescriptive relativism represent the only two viable alternatives to his utilitarianism-with-an-fMRI plugged into it. It's worse still that he doesn't even feel like Bentham and Mill, from whom these ideas originate, are even worthy of meaningful discussion in his book.<br /><br />As has been noted everywhere, Harris' attempt to conduct this end-run around the philosophical literature that he is, consciously or not, merely restating is childish, lazy, and irritating. All that he has ultimately done in his book has been to redefine consequentialist philosophy as science and then to suggest that science, and not philosophy, is what should determine human values. It's both internally incoherent as an argument and a disingenuous shock ploy to sell copies. <br /><br />In defending the book, Harris claims to have addressed all of these criticisms in The Moral Landscape itself. If by "addressing," we mean either indicating that he does not understand them and/or perfunctorily dismissing them (as is the case with Jonathan Haidt, whose points Harris talks straight past, among others), then surely he has. If he feels that he has competently refuted the backbreaking weight of what he is up against, then he seems alone in that belief.<br /><br />Any competent introduction to moral philosophy (James Rachels is a good place to start) will be much more worth your time. If you're concerned about missing out on all the science that Harris brings to bear on the topic (spoiler alert!), don't waste your time. There's passing reference to some psychology and Harris' graduate work with an fMRI. None of it is essential to his argument. The "science" in Harris' subtitle essentially translates to "anything about nature that can be known in principle." It's hard to imagine applying for a grant to fund that.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4087308366382797533" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


